--- title: "Block With Friction" subtitle: Position Control with friction. Using Pole Placement + PD. --- ## Response Analysis ::: {#cell-start-bode .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using CCS using ControlSystems, Plots, LinearAlgebra, RobustAndOptimalControl CCS.setupEnv() contSys = CCS.blockModel.csys(;g = 0, α = 0 , μ = 1, τ =20) plot!(bodeplot(contSys[1,1]),pzmap(contSys)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ::: {.ansi-escaped-output} ```{=html} 
Precompiling CCS...
  12450.0 ms  ✓ CCS
  1 dependency successfully precompiled in 16 seconds. 510 already precompiled.
``` ::: ::: ::: {#start-bode .cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` Starting Bode Plot and Pole/Zero Map ::: ::: It has the shape we expect from a motor + friction. Slow pole for the mass + friction and a faster pole for the current & inductance. Numerically they are: ::: {#4 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} display(eigvals(contSys.A)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display} ``` 3-element Vector{Float64}: -20.0 -1.0 0.0 ``` ::: ::: We see that we start with all the poles in the left-half plane, which is good. ## Pole Placement We can design a controller with pole placement. For some reason pole placement doesn't work for the observer, I use a Kalman Filter with random fast values. ::: {#6 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} observability(contSys.A,contSys.C).isobservable || error("System is not observable") controllability(contSys.A,contSys.B).iscontrollable || error("System is not controllable") ε = 0.01; pp = 15.0; poles_cont = - [pp + ε, pp - ε, pp]; L = real(place(contSys, poles_cont, :c)); poles_obs = poles_cont * 10.0; K = place(contSys, poles_obs, :o) obs_controller = observer_controller(contSys, L, K; direct=false); fsf_controller = named_ss(obs_controller, u = [:ref_S, :ref_V], y = [:u]); ``` ::: We can check the effect of the new controller on the loop ::: {#8 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} closedLoop = feedback( contSys * fsf_controller); print(poles(closedLoop)); setPlotScale("dB") plot!(bodeplot(closedLoop[1,1], 0.1:40), pzmap(closedLoop)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` ComplexF64[-14.990000366343788 + 0.0im, -14.999999266673722 + 0.0im, -15.010000366982666 + 0.0im, -149.99999999999986 + 0.0im, -150.10000000002432 + 0.0im, -149.8999999999607 + 0.0im] ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: We can compare this to the open-loop response in @start-bode. We can see that we achieve unitary gain throughout the whole low-frequency range. We can convert the pole placement controller into the standard PD gain form. ::: {#10 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using DiscretePIDs Ts = 0.02 # sampling time Tf = 2.5; #final simulation time K = L[1]; Ti = 0; Td = L[2] / L[1]; pid = DiscretePID(; K, Ts, Ti, Td); ``` ::: ## Simulation We can simulate this with a motor that only outputs the position: ::: {#12 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} sysreal = ss(contSys.A, contSys.B, [1 0 0], 0.0) ctrl = function (x, t) y = (sysreal.C*x)[] # measurement d = 0 * [1.0] # disturbance r = 2.0 * (t >= 1) # reference # u = pid(r, y) # control signal # u + d # Plant input is control signal + disturbance # u =1 e = x - [r; 0.0; 0.0] e[3] = 0.0 # torque not observable, just ignore it in the final feedback u = -L * e + d u = [maximum([-20.0 minimum([20.0 u])])] end t = 0:Ts:Tf res = lsim(sysreal, ctrl, t) display(plot(res, plotu=true, plotx=true, ploty=false )) ylabel!("u", sp=1); ylabel!("x", sp=2); ylabel!("v", sp=3); ylabel!("T", sp=4); ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: For more stats: ::: {#14 .cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} si = stepinfo(res); plot(si);title!("Step Response") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: We can also simulate it in a SIMULINK-like environment: ::: {#16 .cell freeze='true' execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using FMI, DifferentialEquations fmuPath = abspath(joinpath(@__DIR__, "..","..", "modelica", "ControlChallenges", "ControlChallenges.BlockOnSlope_Challenges.Examples.WithFriction.fmu")) fmu = loadFMU(fmuPath); simData = simulateME( fmu, (0.0, 5.0); recordValues=["blockOnSlope.x", "blockOnSlope.xd", "blockOnSlope.usat"], showProgress=false); unloadFMU(fmu); plot(simData, states=false, timeEvents=false) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: There is a slight difference between the `lsim` simulation and the FMU simulation. I need to recheck some stuff. {{< control target="TutorialBlockWithFriction" code="let Kp = 337; let Kd = 64; function controlFunction(block) { return -( block.x * Kp + block.dx*Kd); }" >}}
